Continuing bird in breeding plumage. Black head, red eye, white necklace white to yellowish-white breast and belly. Back and upper side of wings black with white spots. Beautiful bird. What a treat to see this in San Diego in the summer. First spotted it way out in the water while standing on the sidewalk near Mariners Point Park around 4:00 p.m. It swam north/northeast and under the West Mission Bay Bridge, still staying a good distance from the Mariners Point Park shoreline. I went under the bridge and stayed on it and eventually it started moving closer, until it came very near the shoreline just north of the bridge. Before it went under the bridge it swam along on top of the water, with its head mostly in the water. After it went under the bridge it dove a lot and moved a lot, so staying on it was challenging at times. The photos I took when it came really close by the bridge were taken at 4:40 p.m. It continued to stay near shore as it went south and back under the bridge and then it stayed mostly in one relatively small area preening. So same behavior others have reported at various times in the afternoon this week. This is about where I was standing part of the time as I watched it preening: 32.76734,-117.24464.  It stuck around preening for over 45 minutes and eventually slowly drifted south and went past the chain link fence. Photos.

Locality: New River, Whitethorne to Big Falls Float.
Observation Details: Juvenile.  Very clearly seen and observed for 45 minutes to an hour as close as 15 feet away. The bird was actively feeding in  one to one and half feet of briskly moving water relatively close to shore. I could see him swimming underwater and two inch baitfish leaping out of the water to avoid being eaten. Created quite a wake and bulge on the top of  the water. after feeding it preened for about 20 minutes and was still preening when I left. I observed and photographed laying down on the deck of my paddleboard. Definitely the closest look I have had of a loon. Super cool.

Continuing bird in breeding plumage. Black head, red eye, white necklace white to yellowish-white breast and belly. Back and upper side of wings black with white spots. Beautiful bird. What a treat to see this in San Diego in the summer. First spotted it way out in the water while standing on the sidewalk near Mariners Point Park around 4:00 p.m. It swam north/northeast and under the West Mission Bay Bridge, still staying a good distance from the Mariners Point Park shoreline. I went under the bridge and stayed on it and eventually it started moving closer, until it came very near the shoreline just north of the bridge. Before it went under the bridge it swam along on top of the water, with its head mostly in the water. After it went under the bridge it dove a lot and moved a lot, so staying on it was challenging at times. The photos I took when it came really close by the bridge were taken at 4:40 p.m. It continued to stay near shore as it went south and back under the bridge and then it stayed mostly in one relatively small area preening. So same behavior others have reported at various times in the afternoon this week. This is about where I was standing part of the time as I watched it preening: 32.76734,-117.24464.  It stuck around preening for over 45 minutes and eventually slowly drifted south and went past the chain link fence. Photos.

Media notes: Justin and Carol with Loon
Observation Details: Rescue of the Loon that was unable to fly out of Dix Pond at Matthaei the last few days. When I got to the area about 12:30 Carol and Justin were walking up the trail with the loon covered with Justin’s jacket. They saw it trying to fly out of the pond but it landed on the ground where they rescued it. I had brought a large plastic storage bin and towels just in case. We went back up to my car and put the loon in the bin. Bill joined us. The Loon appeared healthy so it was decided to release at Barton Pond.  Once there Bill released it at the water’s edge. It swam off doing some vocalizing.  I’d like to think it was saying Thank You :)

Observation Details: Observed with one chick. The chick can be no more than 3 days old at this time. In our experience this is the latest we have observed a loon chick to have hatched. When last observed adult loons were still nest sitting. These loons nest on an artificial nest platform and often return to rest there with the chick for extended periods. The chick has the ability to dive, staying submerged for up to 5 seconds. Shortly after we arrived one adult left and was not seen for the remainder of our observations. As it turns out it was the male (identified by its call) that was left attending the chick by itself. Observations are part of the Canadian Lakes Loon Survey

Observation Details: Juvenile.  Very clearly seen and observed for 45 minutes to an hour as close as 15 feet away. The bird was actively feeding in  one to one and half feet of briskly moving water relatively close to shore. I could see him swimming underwater and two inch baitfish leaping out of the water to avoid being eaten. Created quite a wake and bulge on the top of  the water. after feeding it preened for about 20 minutes and was still preening when I left. I observed and photographed laying down on the deck of my paddleboard. Definitely the closest look I have had of a loon. Super cool.

Two mature individuals. Likely male and female. Seem regulars at the lake. Foraging as a pair along the shore about 30-60 feet out. Not impressed by speedboats or swimmers. Approach swimmers up to 20 feet. Dive calmly from speedboats. Astonishingly non-shy. Followed them from kayak for about 1 hour. Went over to self-care in the middle of the lake. Heard calling at night and rarely during the day. Exceptional opportunity for images. I am not sure if this pair has a permanent nest on the lake. If not, will try to have lake association install one.

Two mature individuals. Likely male and female. Seem regulars at the lake. Foraging as a pair along the shore about 30-60 feet out. Not impressed by speedboats or swimmers. Approach swimmers up to 20 feet. Dive calmly from speedboats. Astonishingly non-shy. Followed them from kayak for about 1 hour. Went over to self-care in the middle of the lake. Heard calling at night and rarely during the day. Exceptional opportunity for images. I am not sure if this pair has a permanent nest on the lake. If not, will try to have lake association install one.

Juvenile. Favouring the boathouse end. Only diving to avoid rowers. Some snorkelling but no concerted effort to catch fish. Showing down to a few metres. Attempted to flap at one point but seemed very weak. Hard to be optimistic for this bird’s health in the long term.

Continuing bird. Large low-slung swimmer with large head and dagger-shaped bill. Bill pale blue-gray with dark culmen. Head and neck grayish-brown dorsally, white ventrally. Demarcation between these irregular, with dark extending further forward on lower neck (almost forming an incomplete band). Feathers of back and upper-wing coverts dark-centered with pale edging, showing considerable wear. Iris deep red. Many photos.
Still present.
Still present.

Classic non-breeding plumaged Common Loon. Large and long-bodied. Comparatively large head with flat crown, large dagger-like bill. Overall dark gray-brown dorsally, white ventrally. Bill pale bluish-gray with dark culmen. Demarcation between dark plumage on back of neck and light plumage on front of neck irregular and jagged. Seen up close, eye dark red, feathers on back very dark-centered with medium-gray edges, giving strong scalloped look. That, coupled with the pattern of white above and below eye, suggests a juvenile bird. Photos to be added.

Locality: Rat Branch Boat Ramp, Hampton, Tennessee, US (36.305, -82.119)

Observation Details: As I was walking along the dam to the west PL, I saw a Loon near the Haunted Tower. I was thrilled that it was only ~50 m away. I watched it for awhile, took a few so-so pictures, then continued to the west PL. Forty minutes later, walking back along the dam, the Loon was only 10 m from the shoreline and ~20 m perpendicular distance from the walking path on the dam. I estimated how far the Loon was swimming during each dive. I positioned myself so that I would have the sun at my back and the Loon right in front of me when it surfaced from its next dive. It worked. I got my best picture to date of this magnificent bird in full alternate plumage.  [NOTE: This is the fifth time in five years that I have seen Common Loon at Lk_Yos. I had one in 2017; none in 2018; one in 2019; two last year; and one today.]

Two mature individuals. Likely male and female. Seem regulars at the lake. Foraging as a pair along the shore about 30-60 feet out. Not impressed by speedboats or swimmers. Approach swimmers up to 20 feet. Dive calmly from speedboats. Astonishingly non-shy. Followed them from kayak for about 1 hour. Went over to self-care in the middle of the lake. Heard calling at night and rarely during the day. Exceptional opportunity for images. I am not sure if this pair has a permanent nest on the lake. If not, will try to have lake association install one.

When I arrived there were five common loons fairly close to the boat ramp, swimming in a group. A couple of loons had furrowed brows. While kayaking, I saw loons in groups of 2-3 in different parts of the pond, swimming and diving. While paddling my way back to the ramp, I was half way or more there along the west shore, near the trail that runs along the pond edge, and heard extremely loud loon screeching, sounding distressed coming from the furthest end of the lake (to the north). At the boat ramp, I had my kayak loaded when I heard and saw two loons fighting approximately 200 – 300 yards distant from the boat landing. I took many photos, changing the setting from low to high burst, while the camera autofocus went in and out of focus due to the distance to the loons (35 mm full frame camera, telephoto at 600 mm with 1.4 teleconverter = 840 mm, using crop frame mode for a better view). I also have bands in some photos. Following the fight I have a few photos where it appears there may have been injury to the back of a loon's head (reported to LPC field biologist by the Harris Center). Many photos in addition to those posted here.

Unusual was a 1-yr-old (SY) hanging around off the boat launch. This immature had worn primaries and many worn and old juvenile feathers but appeared to have first alternate (= first winter) face and some body feathers. The nape, hindneck, and most scapulars were worn. This bird is not as worn as many first-summer birds can be. It is unusual to see this age on inland ponds in summer.  Adult seen nw. of launch going out and on return. Pair (banded) with chick nw. of Ram Is. at mouth of Trout Brook. The female fed the chick a small crayfish. Four adults together east of Blueberry Island, two of which were banded. One adult near Rome town beach (unbanded). Two (unbanded pair, male and female by structure) east of Crooked Island (44°33′45″ N  69°51′17″ W). One adult 200 m south of previous. Four together (ultimately six) at 44°33′51″ N  69°49′39″ W (included "double blue" Blue/Blue male banded in 2008). Then five east toward Snake Point: R/Gr, Y/s; Rstripe/Y,?. A pair in this group was far from their chick, which was on the east side of Snake Point. Gravely injured bird seen 300 meters se. of Otter Island at 44°32′48″ N  69°49′56″ W. Damage to this bird's left wing was severe and could have been from a high speed boat hitting it. Another adult was seen near it. Adult in flight landed south of last birds. Two adults and chick at Oak Island (banded male Ydot/silver; Ystripe/Gr; female Y/Y, Y/?). Two adults, one in Pinkhams Cove and another toward Austin Bog. Adult with chick near Austin Bog (44°29′34″ N  69°50′14″ W). Three east of Long Point, one banded (male from Oak Island was here; so a long way from where first seen.  We observed still dependent chicks, one being fed a small crayfish. I will add breeding codes to separate list in atlas blocks where those were seen (but with generic locations)

Locality: New River, Whitethorne to Big Falls Float.
Observation Details: Juvenile.  Very clearly seen and observed for 45 minutes to an hour as close as 15 feet away. The bird was actively feeding in  one to one and half feet of briskly moving water relatively close to shore. I could see him swimming underwater and two inch baitfish leaping out of the water to avoid being eaten. Created quite a wake and bulge on the top of  the water. after feeding it preened for about 20 minutes and was still preening when I left. I observed and photographed laying down on the deck of my paddleboard. Definitely the closest look I have had of a loon. Super cool.

Observation Details: Two mature individuals. Likely male and female. Seem regulars at the lake. Foraging as a pair along the shore about 30-60 feet out. Not impressed by speedboats or swimmers. Approach swimmers up to 20 feet. Dive calmly from speedboats. Astonishingly non-shy. Followed them from kayak for about 1 hour. Went over to self-care in the middle of the lake. Heard calling at night and rarely during the day. Exceptional opportunity for images. I am not sure if this pair has a permanent nest on the lake. If not, will try to have lake association install one.

Locality: Central Michigan University Disc Golf Course area
Observation Details: I watched the loons for just over 30 minutes when I first arrived and they behaved as one would expect; swimming, diving, etc. However, when coming back around from walking around the course they were repeatedly flying to the other side of the pond together. The pair would swim in the direction of the wind, turn around, start 'running' on the water and take off before landing on the other side of the pond. They would then leisurely swim back and repeat. During this, one would occasionally sit up (I think it's called the penguin stance?) and flap its wings facing towards the other loon. The other loon never responded to this. On the fifth flight back, one of the loons did not land. Rather it did a few laps around the pond before flying off to the North-West and then ~15 seconds later it flew back from that direction, over the pond, and then towards the South-East never to be seen again (Or at least for the next ~10 minutes that I was there). The remaining loon began vocalizing more than they had before, mostly the well-known Loon call. Previously they would occasionally make a short and quite whine call. I saw the remaining loon to swim back and fly across the pond three more times with the third time being right as I was leaving.

Observation Details: Seen close to shore in Sunset Cove.  Two of us were looking at the loon, wondering if this might be a Pacific Loon (one had been reported yesterday evening along with Common Loons).  The head was rounded like a Pacific Loon and lacked the 'blocky' appearance the heads of Common Loons usually have.  However ... the neck showed a partial dark collar that gave an uneven separation between the white and dark parts of the neck (but not the same type of white indentation I usually see in a Common Loon).  The bill was heavier and more angular like a Common Loon.  The area around the eyes was white like a Common Loon.  There was no dark chin strap that you usually see in a Pacific Loon.

Observation Details: Caught a large fish and spent nearly a minute working it around so it could be swallowed head first.  It appeared to put the fish, while held by the bill tips, in the water and spin its entire body so the resistance of the water helped move the fish into position.  The loon was not flipping the fish around in the air, but holding the fish in the water while repositioning it.  The loon was sometimes turning in a circular motion while doing this. But it also, especially at first, seemed to be shoving the fish down in the water, from holding it out of the water to pushing down so the loon's entire head was submerged.  I'm guessing it was using the resistance of the water to help reposition the fish, The fish often appeared to be held just by the bill tips, so it could pivot while being shoved and turned in the water.  The fish was not visibly struggling very much- the behavior was not the fish nearly escaping and being re-grabbed. Maybe it was even allowing the fish to try to swim while held to help get it turned into position.

Media notes: Very little sibling rivalry has ever been noted amongst loon offspring. One loon chick calmly waits as its nest mate gets fed.
Observation Details: Documentation of the late season breeding success of a resident pair of loons. We have been observing loons nesting at this location for well over 10 years as part of CLLS and this is the very latest nesting attempt we've seen. Previously this nest site was a natural shoal. Drowned by rising Georgian Bay water levels it continues to host nesting loons on a man-made nest raft. First chick hatched sometime during the afternoon of July 30 with the second sometime overnight July 30 to 31. One adult Loon returns to the nest with the young each evening where they spend most of the night time hours in relative safety

Observation Details: Immature or non-breeding adult

Abbie Tamber & I got permission to check on the pair of breeding adults here.  Genegantslet is a private lake with restricted access.  Last year, we documented that the pair had attempted to nest but a predator got to the eggs.  Members of the lake association confirmed that the pair returned again this year.  They posted a sign to warn lake association members to stay away from the nest.  I figured it was a good time to see if there were any loonlets.  We kayaked the lake but found only one adult.  In talking with our hosts, they confirmed that the 2 adults were last seen about 1 week ago.  The fact that we saw only one adult and no young was not encouraging.  Loons in the Adirondacks have had young since the end of June/early July.  The nest sight is not visible from out on the lake.  Our hosts will update us with any new information.

Observation Details: This loon might be injured, sick or fatigued.  It was first spotted 2 meters offshore.  It seemed focused on preening, digging at one part of it's chest.  It also did a few wing flaps that lifted it erect out of the water.  It then hunted for sand eels, and we watched it hork down a few.  Then it came ashore right where we were sitting, vocalizing quietly. (I learned that loons can't walk, they just scoot).  It came up to.a meter away from us.  It was preening it's chest in that one place (and also a bit on the wing).  Then it just sat there calmly, occasionally trilling quietly.

Observation Details: No loon in Bisson wetland area but one loon was initially observed in main water at dam (south) end. This loon was on alert, holding neck/head high. At that time, no loon appeared to be on the nest. The loon eventually made its way to mid-water in front of the west cove area. I then walked north down Reservoir Rd to the small inlet to see if one of the pair was "hiding" in there, and sure enough, I observed one loon resting quietly. I watched it for several minutes until it started making its way back toward the open water and to the nest. A few minutes later, it met up with its mate, who came out of nowhere, and they took a small swim together toward the "big" island. One loon then made its way back to the nest area and got up on the nest, and the other was resting on the water nearby. The 3rd loon was in the west cove when I left.

Continuing adult breeding plumage. I don’t think I’ve ever gone birding, hoping not to find a bird. But that was the case this morning. Observed closely for over 90 minutes. Gently paddling around the center of the pond between the rod and the train station. Initially, occasionally putting face in water to drink, not feed. It would put the face longer in the water near the fountain. Good sign. It dived and shook wings after. It looked like a move to warn off a juvenile approaching duck. Then later, dove as if to feed near the bank. Seen preening and stretching wings several times after. The right wing didn’t seem to extend fully. Captured in video. Will try to post videos. The only physical issue seems to be right wing. Awkwardly exited pond on the south side to sit in the grass near sidewalk briefly before rapidly returning to the water. Immediately dove twice upon entry. Video

Continuing bird. Large low-slung swimmer with large head and dagger-shaped bill. Bill pale blue-gray with dark culmen. Head and neck grayish-brown dorsally, white ventrally. Demarcation between these irregular, with dark extending further forward on lower neck (almost forming an incomplete band). Feathers of back and upper-wing coverts dark-centered with pale edging, showing considerable wear. Iris deep red. Many photos.

Repeat sighting. Today, first encountered at north end of south pond. It kept diving and surfacing somewhere else, apparently hunting for food while swimming many meters underwater. White below and extending up front of neck to beak. Gray beak, held slightly open. Eye uniformly dark. Will attach photo taken today.

Classic non-breeding plumaged Common Loon. Large and long-bodied. Comparatively large head with flat crown, large dagger-like bill. Overall dark gray-brown dorsally, white ventrally. Bill pale bluish-gray with dark culmen. Demarcation between dark plumage on back of neck and light plumage on front of neck irregular and jagged. Seen up close, eye dark red, feathers on back very dark-centered with medium-gray edges, giving strong scalloped look. That, coupled with the pattern of white above and below eye, suggests a juvenile bird. Photos to be added.

Discovered yesterday by Juliet Berger, stuck at Dix Pond where it did not have enough room to take off (they need some 200 yards of water to do so). We met Carol Poulous taking photos of it, who after we left saw it get out of the water (they can't walk on land because of their extreme rear-placed legs). Carol, Lorri W, Justin and Bill VanderMolen were able to safely put the COLO into a carrier and take him to Barton Pond, releasing him there--hurray, hurray!!! See https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CbeHW02kRCg

When I arrived there were five common loons fairly close to the boat ramp, swimming in a group. A couple of loons had furrowed brows. While kayaking, I saw loons in groups of 2-3 in different parts of the pond, swimming and diving. While paddling my way back to the ramp, I was half way or more there along the west shore, near the trail that runs along the pond edge, and heard extremely loud loon screeching, sounding distressed coming from the furthest end of the lake (to the north). At the boat ramp, I had my kayak loaded when I heard and saw two loons fighting approximately 200 – 300 yards distant from the boat landing. I took many photos, changing the setting from low to high burst, while the camera autofocus went in and out of focus due to the distance to the loons (35 mm full frame camera, telephoto at 600 mm with 1.4 teleconverter = 840 mm, using crop frame mode for a better view). I also have bands in some photos. Following the fight I have a few photos where it appears there may have been injury to the back of a loon's head (reported to LPC field biologist by the Harris Center). Many photos in addition to those posted here.

Twitchell Lake has two breeding pair of Loon.  I'll prefer to them as south & north pair.  The south pair just fledged two young yesterday.  The north pair have left their nest (on a grassy island). They were together preening nearby and it was clear that they had no young.  A failed nesting.  There was another single adult feeding in the lake.  I could see all five adults with my binoculars at one time.  The south pair kept their young under wing much of the time.  I did manage a distant photo of the two young and some shots of a single fledgling riding on the adult's back.

Two adults, two juveniles.  I watched mom working with her babies for over an hour teaching them how to feed themselves.  Sometimes she'd bring up food and give it to them, sometimes she'd come up with food, then as they approached she'd take it under and have them go under to get it, and other times she'd come up without food, then when they came over she'd dive, then they'd dive with her and get their own food.  Very cool experience to watch.

Breeding pair of Common Loons. Every morning I would wake up early and paddle a row boat quietly across this misty, spring fed lake - circling its small island and maneuvering for good shots of these loons while they dove for fish. Sometimes I would wait an agonizing amount of time, holding my heavy lenses at point while they picked at their plumage, knowing full well at the end of their grooming that they would raise their wings high.

Observation Details: Documentation of the late season breeding success of a resident pair of loons. We have been observing loons nesting at this location for well over 10 years as part of CLLS and this is the very latest nesting attempt we've seen. Previously this nest site was a natural shoal. Drowned by rising Georgian Bay water levels it continues to host nesting loons on a man-made nest raft. First chick hatched sometime during the afternoon of July 30 with the second sometime overnight July 30 to 31. One adult Loon returns to the nest with the young each evening where they spend most of the night time hours in relative safety

Observed from eastern shoreline. After ~ 25 minutes of scanning with binocs, finally saw one adult diving in NE area. Loon came close to shoreline and continued diving in SE area of pond. I then noticed a 2nd loon farther out in middle of water. This loon continued diving until meeting up with 1st loon in SE part, at which point both dove together for ~ 15 minutes. One loon then started wing-rowing towards mid-water, where it remained while diving, with the other loon staying in the SE area.

Observation Details: *Rare; continuing bird in high plumage;  calling repeatedly close to shore; photos

*exceptional movement of Common Loons, though not totally unexpected given the conditions; at the beginning of observation period, 5 were on the water, and when I left, 12 more had arrived, making for an exact count of 56 flyovers. Most of the flyovers were between 1:00 and 1:45 pm, during a steady but fairly light rain that immediately preceded the heaviest downpour, after which very few loons were noted as flyovers. All birds were heading in a north/northeasterly direction on the tail of the strong S/SW winds before they shifted drastically. Most flyovers were in groups ranging from 2 to 6 birds. This number of loons may be unprecedented for county standards, and it was an amazing spectacle to witness. Photos of many flyovers, and some of the 17 on the water when the weather broke:

Locality: Pond at North Florida Regional Hospital

Observation Details: Two mature individuals. Likely male and female. Seem regulars at the lake. Foraging as a pair along the shore about 30-60 feet out. Not impressed by speedboats or swimmers. Approach swimmers up to 20 feet. Dive calmly from speedboats. Astonishingly non-shy. Followed them from kayak for about 1 hour. Went over to self-care in the middle of the lake. Heard calling at night and rarely during the day. Exceptional opportunity for images. I am not sure if this pair has a permanent nest on the lake. If not, will try to have lake association install one.

I walked to the tip of Leo's Landing, turned to my left, and was shocked to find this Common Loon less than 50' from me in a very shallow puddle. I did not approach any closer. I snapped a few pictures by holding my cell phone up to my binoculars. It did not seem injured or in distress, though in hindsight I wonder if I should have reported it. When I walked away, I turned around and snapped another picture that shows how it was situated. It did not move from this spot while I was present.

Media notes: Interesting color in a Common Loon, probably an artifact of early morning light - my first impression was that of a Yellow-billed Loon, before I analyzed the rest of the field marks.
Observation Details: One of the Common Loons, by the entrance to Stopsign Cove just east of the dam was quite interesting.  Based on color alone in my photographs, it appeared very much like a Yellow-billed Loon.  However, this appears to be due to the early morning light.  Although the bill appeared very light overall, the culmen is slightly curved, the lower mandible and overall bill did not appear to be heavy enough, the loon was not holding its head slightly upturned like a YBLO usually does, and the back appeared to have a more checkerboard pattern.

Early morning social gathering, likely including the pair on this lake, the pair on Upper Suncook Lake, and one banded loon (this summer) from the newly established middle channel (between Upper and Lower Suncook lakes. All was good between these birds as they swam near one of the islands, but after about 45 minutes, five of them got quite aggressive against one of the other loons, and the group broke up thereafter. This group was subsequently partially reform into a group of four after a period of separation and feeding. One of these was the banded bird mentioned above, this group mostly floating and preening before heading out of range. .

It then made a few short dives while we were watching from the boat at a range of about 30 yards. We observed it putting its head under water several times and wondered if it could be looking for fish because it was not preening. Eventually, it made one last dive before we were unable to relocate it.

One adult loon stayed with its loon chick the entire time, while its possible mate stayed separate, about 100 yards away. During this time the lone parent wailed frequently and it appeared to be due to the bald eagles that were nearby. Otherwise, the lone parent was feeding and preening. The loon chick looked healthy and made several dives to feed, but mostly stayed on the surface.

An adult late-summer social gathering. Three first observed, later another landed to join the party. Another heard overhead, tremolo calls numerous times, possibly because it was close to the area where the eagle was located. It never did join the full group and I wonder if it wasn't staying in close contact with the juvenile that was hatched on the lake, though we did not see it today. After about an hour, after a bout of preening, the loons up and took off.

We watched them all leave—circle and fly off.

Rescue of the Loon that was unable to fly out of Dix Pond at Matthaei the last few days. When I got to the area about 12:30 Carol and Justin were walking up the trail with the loon covered with Justin’s jacket. They saw it trying to fly out of the pond but it landed on the ground where they rescued it. I had brought a large plastic storage bin and towels just in case. We went back up to my car and put the loon in the bin. Bill joined us. The Loon appeared healthy so it was decided to release at Barton Pond.  Once there Bill released it at the water’s edge. It swam off doing some vocalizing.  I’d like to think it was saying Thank You :)
